The photocurrent response of trypsin with different concentrations (2, 5, 8, 10, 20, 50, 100, 200, 500, and 1000 ng mL−1) was investigated under optimal conditions in this study (Fig. 11
                        A). It can be seen that the photocurrent response became more and more intense with the increase in trypsin concentration. The linear equation was A = 2.531lgCtrypsin + 0.101 (R2 = 0.995) as depicted in Fig. 11B, where A represents photocurrent intensity. The detection limit of 0.42 ng mL−1 was low enough to have high sensitivity for trypsin monitoring. According to the results that several previously reported methods for trypsin were compared with our study used (Table 1
                        ), it was proved that the PEC biosensor in the study had very superior performance in trypsin detection.
